      "y": 2626.6489123389833,
      "width": 610.9167175292969,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0r",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 16131753,
      "version": 283,
      "versionNonce": 1434319465,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775191520364,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. A fundamental prerequisite for the attack.\n\n2. Physical Address Mapping: When a page is shared, the virtual address entries for\nboth the spy and the victim map to the same physical page.\n\n3. Cache Interference: Because the Last-Level Cache (LLC) is physically tagged, the\nspy can manipulate the cache state of the victim’s code. Specifically, if the spy\nflushes a memory line from a shared page, it is removed from the cache hierarchy\nfor all processes sharing that physical page.\n\n4. Bypassing ASLR: A key implication of this prerequisite is that the attack is\noblivious to Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR). Since the attack targets\nthe physical address of the shared page rather than the virtual address, the random\nmapping used by the OS does not protect the victim.\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. A fundamental prerequisite for the attack.\n\n2. Physical Address Mapping: When a page is shared, the virtual address entries for both the spy and the victim map to the same physical page.\n\n3. Cache Interference: Because the Last-Level Cache (LLC) is physically tagged, the spy can manipulate the cache state of the victim’s code. Specifically, if the spy flushes a memory line from a shared page, it is removed from the cache hierarchy for all processes sharing that physical page.\n\n4. Bypassing ASLR: A key implication of this prerequisite is that the attack is oblivious to Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR). Since the attack targets the physical address of the shared page rather than the virtual address, the random mapping used by the OS does not protect the victim.\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
